Sixth Avenue, west side, from Washington Place to Waverly Place, showing prominently St. Josephs Roman Catholic Church and its adjoining Sunday School Building.

View 1 shows the absence of the Sixth Avenue Elevated. The tall apartment house at the right is at the S.E. corner of Waverly Place.

View 1: January 17, 1939
View 2: March 15, 1932
View 3: May 5, 1930

P. L. Sperr

Plaque on church reads: "This edifice is the oldest Catholic Church building in Manhattan, erected in 1833"

Sixth Avenue, east side, north from Washington Place to Waverly Place showing this frontage cleared. Subway construction necessitated same. Views 1 and 2 are similar, while No. 3 is from a point of vantage slightly to the north. Outstanding here is the 9 story apartment house, the Van Voorst. This bears No. 125 Waverly Place.

View No. 1: February 24, 1933
View No. 3,2: March 11, 1932

Sixth Avenue, north from a point between Washington and Waverly Places and across the latter (in View 1; north from Waverly Place in View 2) showing prominently the "El" demolition which has progressed to this point. The West 8th Street station of same appears in a skeletal condition against the new Detention House for Women and the clock tower of the Jefferson Market Court. The iron work shack and lot on the right of View 2 are being utilized by subway contractors who are building, at this date, a new subway under the thoroughfare.

January 25, 1939

P. L. Sperr

January 25, 1939

P. L. Sperr

Sixth Avenue, north from a point between Washington and Waverly Places and across the latter as viewed from the west side of the Avenue. Shown under demolition is the "El" structure, long a feature of this vicinity. Work on same has reached Waverly Place. Note also the subway construction shack there. The 9 story apartment house partially shown at the right of Views 1 and 2 is the Van Voorst, No. 123-125 Waverly Place. At the left margin appears the clock tower of the Jefferson Market Court. To the center, on the horizon, is the Empire State Building.
